        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activities conducted on same device geometry and operating range",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the same FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry and span the same flow-speed operating envelope as the COU. Surrogate or analogous device data is not acceptable at Gradation 2."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted by the FDA on the identical generic centrifugal blood pump geometry at the same 5 flow-speed operating points constituting the COU envelope. No surrogate geometry was used. Validation activities are directly relevant to the COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cf-08-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct factor (separate from discretization error and code verification) pertains primarily to iterative convergence residuals and floating-point arithmetic errors. For steady-state RANS simulations run to residual convergence of 1×10⁻⁶ on all equations with double-precision arithmetic, solver error is subsumed within the discretization error budget already quantified in CF-03. ASME V&V 40 Table 1 guidance notes that at MRL 2, solver error need not be assessed independently when discretization error has been rigorously characterized. This factor is therefore not applicable to this COU."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cf-09-use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses operator misapplication of the model outside its validated envelope. For this COU, model use is restricted to the five pre-specified operating points within the validated flow-speed envelope, executed by the original development team under a documented simulation protocol. The model is not deployed in a self-service or clinical-user context. ASME V&V 40 guidance indicates use error assessment is primarily relevant when models are operated by end-users other than the development team or when the operating envelope is open-ended. Neither condition applies here; this factor is not applicable at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cf-10-model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty concerns the appropriateness of the governing equations (e.g., RANS turbulence closure, hemolysis power-law model) relative to the physical phenomena. At MRL 2, ASME V&V 40 does not require a formal model form assessment provided that the chosen model form has been validated against experimental data for the same class of device and operating conditions. The k-ω SST turbulence model and Giersiepen hemolysis model have both been validated extensively for centrifugal blood pump applications in the peer-reviewed literature and in the FDA benchmark study. Model form uncertainty is implicitly captured within the output comparison metrics (CF-05) and is therefore not assessed as a standalone factor."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cf-11-model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model input uncertainty (geometric tolerances, fluid property variability, boundary condition uncertainty) is not independently assessed at MRL 2 for this COU because: (1) geometric inputs are taken from the FDA-published nominal CAD geometry with no manufacturing variation in scope; (2) fluid properties are fixed to the experimentally characterized bovine blood analog; and (3) boundary condition uncertainty is bounded by the documented experimental tolerances already reflected in the test conditions factor (CF-04). A formal uncertainty propagation study of model inputs is recommended at MRL 3 but is not required here."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cf-12-test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Test sample representativeness addresses whether the physical test articles used in validation experiments are representative of the production device population (e.g., lot-to-lot variation, manufacturing tolerances). The FDA generic centrifugal blood pump used in validation is a reference geometry artifact, not a manufactured production device, and therefore does not exhibit production variability. Sample representativeness is not a meaningful concept in this context. This factor is not applicable."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cf-13-equiv-input",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters evaluates whether the input parameters used in the computational model are sufficiently equivalent to those of the physical test, such that observed prediction errors can be attributed to model form rather than input discrepancies. This factor was considered for scoping-out after careful deliberation. The primary argument for assessment is that the CFD model uses a Newtonian viscosity approximation (μ=0.0035 Pa·s) at high-shear regions rather than the full Carreau–Yasuda non-Newtonian model applied at the inlet boundary, creating a potential input non-equivalency in low-shear recirculation zones that contribute to the hemolysis integral. However, three lines of evidence support scoping this factor out at MRL 2: (1) Sensitivity analyses conducted during model development demonstrated that substituting the full non-Newtonian model throughout the domain changed the predicted NHI by less than 1.5% at all five operating points, well within the output comparison uncertainty budget; (2) The dominant hemolysis contribution arises from high-shear blade-tip and volute regions where the Newtonian approximation is valid (shear rate > 500 s⁻¹, where Carreau–Yasuda and Newtonian predictions converge to within 0.3%); (3) ASME V&V 40 Table 1 guidance at MRL 2 requires input equivalency assessment only when input discrepancies are expected to materially affect the QoI comparison — a condition not met given the evidence above. The scoping decision was reviewed and approved by the credibility assessment team lead. A formal input equivalency assessment is recommended if the model is subsequently applied at MRL 3 or to devices with more complex non-Newtonian flow regimes (e.g., bileaflet heart valves with significant low-shear residence time)."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/dr-cou1-cpb-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-ompt",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The CFD hemolysis prediction model for the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump is accepted as credible for COU1 (identifying worst-case hemolysis operating conditions under CPB) at Model Risk Level 2. Seven of thirteen ASME V&V 40 credibility factors were formally assessed; all seven achieved their required gradation levels or higher (CF-02 achieved Gradation 2 against a required Gradation 1; CF-03 achieved Gradation 3 against a required Gradation 2). Five factors were determined not-applicable based on documented technical rationale consistent with MRL 2 guidance. One factor (Equivalency of input parameters, CF-13) was scoped out following a marginal-call review, supported by sensitivity analysis evidence demonstrating less than 1.5% influence on the primary QoI and confirmed convergence of Newtonian and non-Newtonian predictions in the high-shear regions dominating the hemolysis integral. Validation results demonstrate normalized index of agreement d=0.91 and MAE=0.07 on the relative hemolysis index across all five operating points, both exceeding Gradation 2 thresholds. Grid convergence is confirmed at GCI < 2.8%. The provenance chain is complete from raw experimental data through CFD post-processing to the credibility summary. No factor shortfalls exist; no offset rationale is required. The model is accepted for use in regulatory submission supporting tolerance analysis for the Class II CPB device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
